; scheduler.form — the compute organ's offer door: scheduling policy as DATA, one chooser engine.
;
; THE GAP (linux-as-recipes.form, scheduler row):
;   "offer-the-compute-organ-to-competing-recipes; recognition-router.fk already CHOOSES an
;    implementation by measured fitness (RUNS as a recipe) — the scheduling POLICY is a recipe,
;    order/fairness its arms."
;
;   Linux's scheduler duty is not reimplemented — it is COMPOSED from the five axioms
;   (core-axioms.form). To run a cell is to OFFER it (axiom-5), so competing recipes place
;   offers at the compute organ's door; per quantum the policy acknowledges exactly one — or
;   nothing, the honest ack when the queue is empty or every offer is below the floor. The
;   others stay queued. Nothing mutates: a quantum returns the next queue as a value (axiom-3).
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/scheduler.fk · proven: tests/scheduler-band.fk -> 511)
;
;   The POLICY IS DATA, never control flow. One generic chooser engine; each policy is a row
;   (key-field, least-wins, floor, requeue) and the engine never branches on a policy's name:
;
;     fifo         (arrival,  least-wins, 0,     run-to-completion)
;     round-robin  (arrival,  least-wins, 0,     REQUEUE at the tail)
;     priority     (priority, greatest,   0,     run-to-completion)
;     fitness      (fitness,  greatest,   floor, run-to-completion)
;
;   1. OFFER       sched-offer / sched-place: a cell presents (name arrival priority fitness)
;      at the door — it carries its measured fitness through the interface it offers
;      (axiom-4); the policy reads the offer, never reaches into the cell.
;   2. ORDER arm   sched-key / sched-better?: the row says WHICH field ranks and WHICH
;      direction wins; ties keep the earlier-queued offer (stable, no thrash).
;   3. FAIL-FAST   sched-passes?: an offer below the row's floor is never acknowledged —
;      recognition-router's carry-no-weak-signal, here as starvation-by-policy made visible.
;   4. ACKNOWLEDGE sched-ack: exactly one offer, or () = nothing — axiom-5's ack discipline
;      (nothing/0/1/node) IS the scheduling decision.
;   5. QUANTUM     sched-step / sched-trace: the chosen offer runs; the fairness arm decides
;      its return — requeue re-offers it at the tail with a fresh stamp from the queue's own
;      clock (one past the latest arrival), so round-robin is FIFO + requeue: fairness
;      emerging from queue discipline, not a special engine path.
;
; ONE ENGINE, PROVEN: the band builds offers FROM recognition-router readings (each presents
;   its rr-strength as its fitness) and shows the fitness row acknowledges exactly the offer
;   rr-route routes — recognition-router's max-over-a-floor select is the (fitness, greatest,
;   floor) row of this engine. Same queue under fifo vs priority yields different but
;   each-correct orders: the policy data is the only variable. Empty queue acks nothing.
;
; KIN: recognition-router.fk (the fitness-chooser this generalizes) · champion-challenger.fk
;   (authority flips on proven competition) · host-kernel.form os-feature-coverage (scheduler =
;   axiom-5 + sovereignty) · substrate-phase.fk (state threads as values, no mutation).
;
; Proof: cd form && ./validate.sh form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/recognition-router.fk \
;   form-stdlib/scheduler.fk form-stdlib/tests/scheduler-band.fk        -> 511, 0 divergent
;
; THE ROW SHAPE READS BOTH DIRECTIONS (2026-06-11): afferent-priority.fk delivers
;   multiple pending unsolicited offers through sched-ack — POSIX number-order IS the
;   fifo row's data read over line numbers; IRQ priority IS the priority row's data
;   read over levels (proven row-for-row: tests/afferent-priority-band.fk -> 1023,
;   three-way; live: scripts/hati_os_kernel_audit.sh section 23). Afferent delivery and
;   efferent scheduling are two readings of ONE policy discipline — the
;   signals+interrupts move, one level up.
